FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, BOVINE - TURKEY (THRACE) (04)
****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Fri 13 Apr 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Department for Environment, Food and
Rural Affairs (DEFRA), International disease
monitoring: Preliminary outbreak assessments,
Ref: VITT 1200/FMD-Turkey, 12 Apr 2007 [edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/monitoring/pdf/fmd-turkey120407.pdf>

Foot and Mouth Disease � Turkey � Thrace Region
-----------------------------------------------
1. Disease Report
An outbreak of Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD type
O) was reported in early April 2007 in cattle at
Evrese in Cannakale (Thrace Region � European
part of Turkey). This new outbreak was said to be
due to the unreported movement of cattle from
Adapazari, Sakarya province (where there were 2
outbreaks of FMD). The disease was then spread
locally through the use of common pastures for
grazing and cut feed and also through the visits
of a local private veterinarian (European Commission, 2007).
2. Situation Assessment
The veterinary authorities in Turkey maintain a
programme of routine vaccination against FMD
(serotypes O, A and Asia1) which are endemic in
Anatolia � the Asian part of Turkey. This
outbreak occurred close to earlier outbreaks in
sheep and cattle reported to OIE in early 2007
(OIE, 2007a; OIE, 2007b) and outlined in Defra's
preliminary outbreak assessment (Defra, 2007).
These previous outbreaks occurred in western
Turkey [map available at the above URL. - Mod.AS]
and were caused by FMD types O and A (strain A
Iran 05). The location of this latest outbreak of
FMD Type O in European Turkey is also close to
the borders of the EU member states of Greece and
Bulgaria. This outbreak highlights the potential
risks for the spread of FMD into unaffected areas
in the region through uncontrolled movements of susceptible animals.
3. Conclusion
The likelihood of the introduction of FMD by
legal trade from Turkey to the UK before and
after this outbreak is considered negligible
because imports of susceptible animals and their
products are banned. The likelihood of FMD virus
being introduced by illegal imports remains
present and is difficult to estimate. The
importance of ensuring that enforcement agencies
are vigilant and that a ban on swill feeding is
effectively applied is again emphasised. We do
not intend to carry out and publish a full risk
assessment on this outbreak but will continue to monitor the situation.
4. References
Defra, (2007). Foot and Mouth disease, Turkey - an update.
<http://defraweb/animalh/diseases/monitoring/pdf/fmdturkey010307.pdf>.
European Commission. (2007). Foot and mouth
disease outbreak in Turkey � Thrace region.
Urgent Fax No 6 (10 Apr 2007 15:30). Brussels D1 BVG (07) D/410893.
OIE. (2007a). Foot and mouth disease, Turkey. OIE
Alert Message TUR 28-02-07. Received by e-mail 28
Feb 2007 [see ref 20070301.0726]
OIE. (2007b). Foot and mouth disease, Turkey. OIE
Alert Message TUR 10-01-07. Received by e-mail 10
Jan 2007 [see ref 20070112.0142].
